300,000,000 while Pakistan has 80,000,000, but a Pakistan
official with whom we traveled
said that all the really good
soldiers in World Wars I as well as II came from Pakistan,
and that in the event of war between the two countries
Pakistan would win despite the greater number of Indians.
From what I have seen of the latter I would be inclined to
agree with him.
The Kashmir dispute may be settled by a
plebiscite
conducted by the U.N. but so far Nehru has been
unwilling to abide by any such procedure because he knows that
in an honest election India would lose.
But unless that
question is settled soon there may be an outbreak of war
between
the tro countries.
I hope the foregoing hasn't bored you.
I knew so
little about the countries and
problems and all explanations
have been so complicated that I
thought you might be interested
in a brief - perhaps over-simplified - description.
If I can finish my work here in time will fly back
to Honkong to join Debby and Hebe.
If not I will join
them
here at Tokyo on February 17th and go on with them to Midway
and Honolulu.
Incidentally, because of the dateline of course,
the scheduled time of arrival in Honolulu is two hours earlier
then the departure time from Tokyo.
This plan is slightly different than our original
itinerary but we hope to travel westward from Honolulu through
Wake, Guam, Manila to Singapore and Batavia.
Bond left Hongkong
the day after I did for Menila where he was to meet George
McClelland (whose sister married Bill Barrett's brother)
and
go on to Batavia for talks about the extension of PAA service
from Singapore to Batavia.
If they are successful we may be
able to fly PAA all the way.
As ever,
н. м. В.
